[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] In computer systems, an **access token** contains the security credentials for a login session and identifies the user, the user's groups, the user's privileges, and, in some cases, a particular application.*"RFC 6749 - The OAuth 2.0 Authorization Framework".
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] *RFC Editor*.* In some instances, one may be asked to enter an access token (e.g.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] 40 random characters) rather than the usual password (it therefore should be kept secret just like a password).
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] An *access token* is an object encapsulating the security identity of a process or thread.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] A token is used to make security decisions and to store tamper-proof information about some system entity.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] While a token is generally used to represent only security information, it is capable of holding additional free-form data that can be attached while the token is being created.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Tokens can be duplicated without special privilege, for example to create a new token with lower levels of access rights to restrict the access of a launched application.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] An access token is used by Windows when a process or thread tries to interact with objects that have security descriptors (*securable objects*).
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] In Windows, an access token is represented by the system object of type `Token`.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] An access token is generated by the logon service when a user logs on to the system and the credentials provided by the user are authenticated against the authentication database.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] The authentication database contains credential information required to construct the initial token for the logon session, including its user id, primary group id, all other groups it is part of, and other information.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] The token is attached to the initial process created in the user session and inherited by subsequent processes created by the initial process.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Whenever such a process opens a handle to any resource which has access control enabled, Windows reconciles the data in the target object's security descriptor with the contents of the current effective access token.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] The result of this access check evaluation is an indication of whether any access is allowed and, if so, what operations (read, write/modify, etc.) the calling application is allowed to perform.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Primary tokens can only be associated to processes, and they represent a process's security subject.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Processes initially inherit a copy of the parent process's primary token.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Impersonation is a security concept implemented in Windows NT that allows a server application to temporarily "be" the client in terms of access to secure objects.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] , same as impersonation but extended to remote systems to which the server connects (through the preservation of credentials).
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] The client can choose the maximum impersonation level (if any) available to the server as a connection parameter.
[src:secrets-vaulting/access-token] Impersonation tokens are usually created and associated to the current thread implicitly, by IPC mechanisms such as DCE RPC, DDE and named pipes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] A **credential** is a piece of any document that details a qualification, competence, or authority issued to an individual by a third party with a relevant or *de facto* authority or assumed competence to do so.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Examples of credentials include academic diplomas, academic degrees, certifications, security clearances, identification documents, badges, passwords, user names, keys, powers of attorney, and so on.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Sometimes publications, such as scientific papers or books, may be viewed as similar to credentials by some people, especially if the publication was peer reviewed or made in a well-known journal or reputable publisher.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] A person holding a credential is usually given documentation or secret knowledge (*e.g.,* a password or key) as proof of the credential.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Sometimes this proof (or a copy of it) is held by a third, trusted party.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] While in some cases a credential may be as simple as a paper membership card, in other cases, such as diplomas, it involves the presentation of letters directly from the issuer of the credential its faith in the person representing them in a negotiation or meeting.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Counterfeiting of credentials is a constant and serious problem, irrespective of the type of credential.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] A great deal of effort goes into finding methods to reduce or prevent counterfeiting.In general, the greater the perceived value of a credential, the more significant the problem of counterfeiting, and the greater the lengths to which the issuer must go to prevent fraud.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] In diplomacy, credentials, also known as a letter of credence, are documents that ambassadors, diplomatic ministers, plenipotentiaries, and chargés d'affaires provide to the government to which they are accredited, for the purpose, chiefly, of communicating to the latter the envoy's diplomatic rank.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] It also contains a request that full credence be accorded to his official statements.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Until his credentials have been presented and found in proper order, an envoy receives no official recognition.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] The credentials of an ambassador or minister plenipotentiary are signed by the head of state, those of a chargé d'affaires by the foreign minister.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Diplomatic credentials are granted and withdrawn at the pleasure of the issuing authority, based on widely varying criteria.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] A receiving government may reject a diplomat’s credentials by declining to receive them, but in practice this rarely happens.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] In medicine, the process of credentialing is a detailed review of all permissions granted a medical doctor, physician assistant or nurse practitioner at every institution at which he or she has worked in the past, to determine a risk profile for them at a new institution.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] It vets the practitioner for both receiving practice insurance and the ability to bill to insurance for patient care.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] As well, it certifies legal and administrative body requirements, such as the Joint Commission.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Medical practitioners must also have credentials in the form of licenses issued by the government of the jurisdictions in which they practice, which they obtain after suitable education, training, and/or practical experience.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Most medical credentials are granted for a practice specific group.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] They may also be withdrawn in the event of fraud or malpractice by their holders.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Typically they require continuing education validation and renewal to continue practice.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Information systems commonly use credentials to control access to information or other resources.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] The classic combination of a user's account number or name and a secret password is a widely used example of IT credentials.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] An increasing number of information systems use other forms of documentation of credentials, such as biometrics (fingerprints, voice recognition, retinal scans), X.509, public key certificates, and so on.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Credentials in cryptography establish the identity of a party to communication.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Usually they take the form of machine-readable cryptographic keys and/or passwords.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Cryptographic credentials may be self-issued, or issued by a trusted third party; in many cases the only criterion for issuance is unambiguous association of the credential with a specific, real individual or other entity.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Cryptographic credentials are often designed to expire after a certain period, although this is not mandatory.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] An X.509 public key certificate is an example of a cryptographic credential.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Operators of vehicles such as automobiles, boats, and aircraft must have credentials in the form of government-issued licenses in many jurisdictions.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Often the documentation of the license consists of a simple card or certificate that the operator keeps on his person while operating the vehicle, backed up by an archival record of the license at some central location.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Licenses are granted to operators after a period of successful training and/or examination.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] This type of credential often requires certification of good health and may also require psychological evaluations and screening for substance abuse.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Operator licenses often expire periodically and must be renewed at intervals.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Renewal may simply be a formality, or it may require a new round of examinations and training.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] In military and government organizations, and some private organizations, a system of compartmentalizing information exists to prevent the uncontrolled dissemination of information considered to be sensitive or confidential.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Persons with a legitimate need to have access to such information are issued *security clearances,* which can be tracked and verified to ensure that no unauthorized persons gain access to protected information.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Security clearances are among the most carefully guarded credentials.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Often they are granted to individuals only after a lengthy investigation and only after their need to have access to protected information has been adequately justified to the issuing authority.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] The most elaborate security-clearance systems are found in the world's military organizations.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Some credentials of this type are considered so sensitive that their holders are not even permitted to acknowledge that they have them (except to authorized parties).
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Documentation of security clearances usually consists of records kept at a secure facility and verifiable on demand from authorized parties.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Security clearances are regularly withdrawn when they are no longer justified, or when the person holding them is determined to be too great a security risk.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] In many democratic nations, press credentials are not required at the national or federal level for any publication of any kind.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] However, individual corporations, and certain government or military entities require press credentials, such as a press pass, as a formal invitation to members of the press which grants them rights to photographs or videos, press conferences, or interviews.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Press credentials indicate that a person has been verified as working for a known publication, and holding a press pass typically allows that person special treatment or access rights.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Some governments impose restrictions on who may work as a journalist, requiring anyone working for the press to carry government-issued credentials.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Restricting press credentials can be problematic because of its limitations on freedom of the press, particularly if government leaders selectively grant, withhold, or withdraw press credentials to disallow critique of government policy.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Any press coverage published under governments that restrict journalism in this way is often treated with skepticism by others, and may not be considered any more truthful or informative than propaganda.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Some trades and professions in some jurisdictions require special credentials of anyone practicing the trade or profession.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] These credentials may or may not be associated with specific competencies or skills.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] In some cases, they exist mainly to control the number of people who are allowed to exercise a trade or profession, in order to control salaries and wages.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Persons acting as merchants, freelancers, etc., may require special credentials in some jurisdictions as well.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Here again, the purpose is mainly to control the number of people working in this way, and sometimes also to track them for tax-reporting or other purposes like people evaluation.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Documentation of academic and professional credentials usually consists of a printed, formal document.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] The issuing institution often maintains a record of the credential as well.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Academic credentials are normally valid for the lifetime of the person to whom they are issued.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Acquisition of these credentials often leads to increased economic mobility and work opportunity, especially for low-income people.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] A general term for academic credentials in the form of a resume is Curriculum vitae, often abbreviated as CV.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] Titles are credentials that identify a person as belonging to a specific group, such as nobility or aristocracy, or a specific command grade in the military, or in other largely symbolic ways.
[src:secrets-vaulting/credential] They may or may not be associated with specific authority, and they do not usually attest to any specific competence or skill (although they may be associated with other credentials that do).
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] An **environment variable** is a user-definable value that can affect the way running processes will behave on a computer.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are part of the environment in which a process runs.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] For example, a running process can query the value of the TEMP environment variable to discover a suitable location to store temporary files, or the HOME or USERPROFILE variable to find the directory structure owned by the user running the process.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] They were introduced in their modern form in 1979 with Version 7 Unix, so are included in all Unix operating system flavors and variants from that point onward including Linux and macOS.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] From PC DOS 2.0 in 1982, all succeeding Microsoft operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, and OS/2 also have included them as a feature, although with somewhat different syntax, usage and standard variable names.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In all Unix and Unix-like systems, as well as on Windows, each process has its own separate set of environment variables.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] By default, when a process is created, it inherits a duplicate run-time environment of its parent process, except for explicit changes made by the parent when it creates the child.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] At the API level, these changes must be done between running `fork` and `exec`.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Alternatively, from command shells such as bash, a user can change environment variables for a particular command invocation by indirectly invoking it via `env` or using the `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLE=VALUE <command>` notation.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] A running program can access the values of environment variables for configuration purposes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Shell scripts and batch files use environment variables to communicate data and preferences to child processes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] They can also be used to store temporary values for reference later in a shell script.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] However, in Unix, non-exported variables are preferred for this as they do not leak outside the process.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, an environment variable that is changed in a script or compiled program will only affect that process and possibly child processes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The parent process and any unrelated processes will not be affected.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Similarly, changing or removing a variable's value inside a DOS or Windows batch file will change the variable for the duration of `COMMAND.COM`or `CMD.EXE`'s existence, respectively.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, the environment variables are normally initialized during system startup by the system init startup scripts, and hence inherited by all other processes in the system.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Users can, and often do, augment them in the profile script for the command shell they are using.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Microsoft Windows, each environment variable's default value is stored in the Windows Registry or set in the `AUTOEXEC.BAT` file.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] On Unix, a setuid program is given an environment chosen by its caller, but it runs with different authority from its caller.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The dynamic linker will usually load code from locations specified by the environment variables `$LD_LIBRARY_PATH` and `$LD_PRELOAD` and run it with the process's authority.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] If a setuid program did this, it would be insecure, because its caller could get it to run arbitrary code and hence misuse its authority.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] For this reason, libc unsets these environment variables at startup in a setuid process. setuid programs usually unset unknown environment variables and check others or set them to reasonable values.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In general, the collection of environment variables function as an associative array where both the keys and values are strings.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The interpretation of characters in either string differs among systems.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] When data structures such as lists need to be represented, it is common to use a colon (common on Unix and Unix-like) or semicolon-delineated (common on Windows and DOS) list.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The variables can be used both in scripts and on the command line.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] They are usually referenced by putting special symbols in front of or around the variable name.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] By convention, names of environment variables are normally expressed in all capital letters.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] This helps keep environment variables distinctly different from other variables and identifiers used in programming codes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Nevertheless, note that case sensitivity in environment variable names differs between operating systems.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] That is, Unix-like operating systems are case-sensitive with respect to environment variable names, while DOS, OS/2, and Windows are not case-sensitive.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In most Unix and Unix-like command-line shells, an environment variable's value is retrieved by placing a `$` sign before the variable's name.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] If necessary, the name can also be surrounded by braces.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the names of environment variables are case-sensitive.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The command **`env`** displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The command **`printenv`** can also be used to print a single variable by giving that variable name as the sole argument to the command.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters such as `COMMAND.COM` and `CMD.EXE`, an environment variable is retrieved by placing a `%` sign before and after it.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters as well as their API, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The environment variable named `HOMEDRIVE` contains the drive letter (plus its trailing `:` colon) of the user's home directory, whilst `HOMEPATH` contains the full path of the user's home directory within that drive.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The command **`SET`** (with no arguments) displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Windows NT and later `set` can also be used to print all variables whose name begins with a given prefix by giving the prefix as the sole argument to the command.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In PowerShell, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The commands `env` and `set` can be used to set environment variables and are often incorporated directly into the shell.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The following commands can also be used, but are often dependent on a certain shell.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] A few simple principles govern how environment variables achieve their effect.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are local to the process in which they were set.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] If two shell processes are spawned and the value of an environment variable is changed in one, that change will not be seen by the other.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] When a child process is created, it inherits all the environment variables and their values from the parent process.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Usually, when a program calls another program, it first creates a child process by forking, then the child adjusts the environment as needed and lastly the child replaces itself with the program to be called.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] This procedure gives the calling program control over the environment of the called program.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In Unix shells, variables may be assigned without the **`export`** keyword.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Variables defined in this way are displayed by the **`set`** command, but are *not* true environment variables, as they are stored only by the shell and are unknown to all other processes.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The `printenv` command will not display them, and child processes do not inherit them.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The persistence of an environment variable can be session-wide or system-wide.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] The **`SET`** command without any arguments displays all environment variables along with their values; **`SET " "`**, zero or more spaces, will include internal variables too.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In `CMD.EXE`, it is possible to assign local variables that will not be global using the **`SETLOCAL`** command and **`ENDLOCAL`** to restore the environment.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] In PHP the `putenv()` function should be used.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Contains a colon-separated list of directories that the shell searches for commands that do not contain a slash in their name (commands with slashes are interpreted as file names to execute, and the shell attempts to execute the files directly).
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] is often used for convenience in various shell scripts (and other contexts).
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Using the environment variable also gives the user the possibility to point to another directory.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] This variable points to the current directory.
[src:secrets-vaulting/environment-variable-p01] Equivalent to the output of the command pwd when called without arguments.
